{{Infobox officeholder | name = | office = Comite International des Sports des Sourds | order = 7th president of | honorific_suffix = [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] | country = {{US}} | predecessor = [[John M. Lovett]] | successor = [[Craig Crowley]] | termend = 2009 | termstart = 2003 | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1953|5|15}} | birth_place = [[Washington D.C.]], [[US]] | death_date = | death_place = }}
'''Donalda Ammons Kay''' (born 15 May 1953) is an American educator and author. She served as a teacher at several deaf schools in United States. Donalda Kay Ammons was also the former President of the [[Comite International des Sports des Sourds]] from 2003 to 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deaflympics.com/icsd.asp?presidents|title=ICSD {{!}} Deaflympics|website=www.deaflympics.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref>
== Biography == Donalda Ammons was born on 15 May 1953 and raised in [[Washington D.C.]] from an all-deaf family. She graduated from the [[Maryland School for the Deaf]] and also went on to teach in that school for three years. In 1970, she attended [[Gallaudet University]] and received her BA in Social Philosophy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.discoveringdeafworlds.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=275&ml=3&mlt=yoo_royalplaza&tmpl=component&Itemid=80|title=DDW Board Profiles - Donalda Ammons, Ph.D.|last=Administrator|website=www.discoveringdeafworlds.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref>
In 1996, she was honoured as the Gallaudet Distinguished Professor of the Year.{{citation needed|date=November 2017}}
== Services to the deaf == As a deaf person herself, Donalda Ammons Kay has been an educator in many deaf schools. In 1977, she has taught at the Maryland School for the Deaf for three years. She has also taught Spanish in the department of foreign languages and literatures at [[Gallaudet University]], a university serving the deaf.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dwu.org/single-post/2014/03/16/16-of-31-Dr-Donalda-Ammons|title=Deaf Women United|website=Deaf Women United|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://videocatalog.gallaudet.edu/?video=17324|title=Gallaudet Video Presents Links with Dr. Donalda Ammons - Gallaudet University |last=University|first=Gallaudet|website=videocatalog.gallaudet.edu|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deaflympics.com/news.asp?1065|title=News {{!}} Deaflympics|website=www.deaflympics.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref>
== Deaflympics == Ammons Kay had been a member of the [[Comite International des Sports des Sourds]] since 1997. She was appointed as the 4th Secretary-general of the ICSD in 1997 and she was the only woman to have held the post of secretary-general of the CISS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deaflympics.com/icsd.asp?secretary-generals|title=ICSD {{!}} Deaflympics|website=www.deaflympics.com|language=en|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://panamdes.com/history/|title=History – Historia|date=2012-07-11|work=PANAMDES|access-date=2017-11-01|language=en-US}}</ref>
Donalda Ammons became the 7th president of the [[International Committee of Sports for the Deaf|Comité International des Sports des Sourds]] in 2003 (as a stand in President from 2003-2005) following the untimely death of the existing president, [[John M. Lovett|John Michael Lovett]]. She was officially elected as the 7th president of the Committee in 2005 and became the first woman to be elected President of the [[Comite International des Sports des Sourds]]. She served as the President of the ICSD from 2003 to 2009.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deaflympics.com/icsd.asp?1407|title=42nd Congress of the ICSD {{!}} Deaflympics|last=|first=|date=|website=www.deaflympics.com|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref>
